# Database Design

## Naming Conventions

- Tables: `snake_case`, plural nouns (`orders`, `order_items`)
- Columns: `snake_case` (`created_at`, `order_status`)
- Primary keys: `id` (auto-generated) or `<table>_id` for composite keys
- Foreign keys: `<referenced_table>_id` (e.g., `customer_id`)
- Indexes: `idx_<table>_<columns>` (e.g., `idx_orders_customer_id`)
- Constraints: `pk_<table>`, `fk_<table>_<ref>`, `uq_<table>_<columns>`, `chk_<table>_<rule>`
- Use lowercase identifiers exclusively (avoids quoting issues across databases)

## Data Types

- Use the most specific type: `BOOLEAN` not `SMALLINT`, `DATE` not `VARCHAR`
- Timestamps: `TIMESTAMPTZ` (with timezone) for events; `DATE` for calendar dates
- Money: `NUMERIC(precision, scale)`, never `FLOAT` or `DOUBLE`
- UUIDs: `UUID` type where supported, otherwise `CHAR(36)`
- Text: `VARCHAR(n)` with explicit length for bounded fields; `TEXT` for unbounded
- Enums: Prefer `VARCHAR` with CHECK constraint over database-native ENUMs (easier to migrate)

## Normalization

- Normalize to 3NF as the baseline
- Denormalize selectively for read performance, document the trade-off
- Every table must have a primary key
- Avoid nullable foreign keys where possible; use junction tables instead

## Constraints

- Primary key on every table (non-negotiable)
- Foreign keys for all relationships with appropriate `ON DELETE` action
- NOT NULL on columns that must always have a value
- CHECK constraints for domain rules (e.g., `price > 0`)
- UNIQUE constraints for business-unique fields (email, SKU)
- Default values where a sensible default exists

## Migration-Friendly Design

- Prefer additive changes (add column, add table) over destructive changes
- Add columns as nullable first, backfill, then add NOT NULL constraint
- Never rename columns in a single migration; use add-migrate-drop pattern
- Always include `IF NOT EXISTS` / `IF EXISTS` guards
- Test migrations against a copy of production data

## Anti-Patterns

- Entity-Attribute-Value (EAV) tables -- use JSONB for flexible schemas
- Single-column primary keys that carry business meaning (use surrogate keys)
- Polymorphic associations without a discriminator
- Storing comma-separated values in a single column

